Blessed be Thou for all the joy—  
for honey-gold mornings, for laughter’s buoy,  
for the hush of rain on thirsty trees,  
and the hush within, when worries cease.  

Blessed for petals that unfold in sun,  
for the breath before the song’s begun,  
for the hope stitched into a newborn’s cry,  
and the quiet courage to say goodbye.  

For hands that hold and voices that heal,  
for every sorrow joy can steal,  
for the dance of dusk on window panes,  
and mercy blooming in our pains.  

Blessed be Thou, who shapes the light,  
who gifts us stars to split the night,  
who teaches hearts to sing and soar—  
blessed be Thou, forevermore.

Blessed be Thou for all the joy—
for morning’s honeyed light,
for petals opening in silent praise,
for laughter threading through the hush of dusk.

Blessed be Thou for the breath that stirs the willow,
for the small hands tugging at hope,
for the hush that follows thunder,
for the dance of fireflies in the garden’s gentle gloom.

Blessed be Thou for the song carried on the wind,
for hearts that mend and bloom anew,
for every kindness, bright and trembling,
that flickers soft in the shadowed hours.

O, in all the world’s turning,
let me greet each dawn with thanks;
let joy be the lamp I carry,
blessing every step along the way.

O God! Thou art my God alone;
In silent dawns, my soul has known
A yearning deep, a whispered plea,
A desert thirst for mystery.

No idol shade, nor fleeting flame,
Can bear the weight of sacred name;
Within the hush, my spirit calls—
You echo soft through empty halls.

When shadows press and doubts abound,
Your gentle presence wraps me round;
No friend or kin, nor star above,
Could match the depth of holy love.

So here I stand, in awe, undone;
By grace revealed, by mercy won;
O God! Thou art my God alone—
My heart, Your altar, Yours alone.

Please spare me your secrets—
let them curl in your palms like sleeping cats,
let their shadows dance in the hollow of your chest
where my words cannot reach.

I have built my walls of quiet,
mortared with peace and a longing for gentle mornings;
I have learned the ache of carrying
stories that are not my own.

Let the moon keep your confessions,
let the night bear your whispers away,
for I am not the riverbed for every sorrow,
nor the lock for every key.

Give me laughter, soft as dandelion seeds,
give me silences unbroken by ache—
for tonight, I wish only for my own company,
my heart unburdened, my soul in repose.
